04720nam a22007335i 9783110767490DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022932905  a97831107674907 a10.1515/97831107674902doi  a(DE-B1597)600760  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE1 aRies, Eva, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrecarious Flânerie and the Ethics of the Self in Contemporary Anglophone Fiction /cEva Ries. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VIII, 298 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBuchreihe der Anglia / Anglia Book Series ,x0340-5435 ;v7600tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- t1 The Return of the Flâneur -- t2 Flânerie and its Discontents -- t3 Michel Foucault’s Ethics of the Self -- t4 Judith Butler’s Precarious Subjects -- t5 Synopsis: Ethical Subjects and the Flânerie Text -- t6 The End of Flânerie? The Sovereign Subject and Precarious City Life in Ian McEwan’s Saturday -- t7 Flânerie as Technique of the Self -- t8 City Matters: Affect and Media in Precarious Performances of Subjectivity -- t9 Conclusion -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEven though the literary trope of the flâneur has been proclaimed ‘dead’ on several occasions, it still proves particularly lively in contemporary Anglophone fiction. This study investigates how flânerie takes a belated ‘ethical turn’ in its more recent manifestations by negotiating models of ethical subjectivity. Drawing on Michel Foucault’s writings on the ‘aesthetics of existence’ as well as Judith Butler’s notion of precariousness as conditio humana, it establishes a link between post-sovereign models of subject formation and a paradoxical constellation of flânerie, which surfaces most prominently in the work of Walter Benjamin. By means of detailed readings of Ian McEwan’s Saturday, Siri Hustvedt’s The Blindfold, Teju Cole’s Open City, Dionne Brand’s What We All Long For and Robin Robertson’s The Long Take, Or a Way to Lose More Slowly, this book traces how the ambivalence of flânerie and its textual representation produces ethical norms while at the same time propagating the value of difference by means of disrupting societal norms of sameness. Precarious Flânerie and the Ethics of the Self in Contemporary Anglophone Fiction thus shows that the flânerie text becomes a medium of ethical critique in post-postmodern times.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022)  aaesthetics of existence.  aflâneuse/flâneur.  aperformative turn.  atechnique of the self.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993738oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831107675200 cprintz978311076747640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311076749040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110767490423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110767490/original  a978-3-11-099375-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishb2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2022  aZDB-23-DKUb2022